# pattern_peaks.psv — sidelobe peak envelope digitized from scanned pattern charts
# Source: NASA CR-159703, R.E. Collin & L.R. Gabel, "Low sidelobe level low-cost earth station
#         antennas for the 12 GHz broadcasting satellite service", Sept 1979 (Case Western Reserve Univ.)
#         https://ntrs.nasa.gov/api/citations/19800004009/downloads/19800004009.pdf
# Method: pages rendered at 400 dpi (PyMuPDF), chart-only crops read visually; axis calibration from the
#         -12/-24/-36 dB (or -10/-20/-30 dB) y-ticks and the +/-3-degree x-grid labels; levels referenced
#         to the main-beam apex (= 0 dB); peaks read against the 1-dB chart fine lines where visible.
# page = 1-based page number in the PDF file (report-printed page = pdf_page - 7).
# Angles signed as drawn on the charts (left of boresight = negative). Both halves recorded; asymmetry is real
# (residual surface error, mixer-stub scatter — see report pp. 59-60, 68).
# uncertainty_db is the level uncertainty; angle uncertainty is +/-0.3 deg (+/-0.5 deg where noted).
# Antennas: spun-aluminum prime-focus paraboloids, f/D = 0.38 nominal.
#   1.22 m: f = 0.457 m, D/lambda ~ 49 at 12.1 GHz.  1.83 m: f = 0.6985 m, D/lambda ~ 73 at 12 GHz.
# Feeds: "waveguide" = manufacturer button-hook rectangular waveguide feed + 0.216 m flat vertex plate
#        (as-delivered config); "kumar" = Kumar coaxial-ring hybrid feed, ~20 dB edge taper, vertex plate
#        replaced by machined paraboloidal section. defocus = fe, feed distance from vertex (m).
# Half-power beamwidths read from the same charts (step-recorder resolution limits accuracy):
#   cut 122_wg_h_120:        HPBW ~ 2.2 +/- 0.4 deg (poor focusing; text gain 37.2 dB vs 41 dB spec)
#   cut 122_kumar_C_h_121:   HPBW ~ 1.5 +/- 0.3 deg (report text states measured 3 dB beamwidth = 1.7 deg; gain 41.4 dB)
#   cut 122_kumar_D_e_121:   HPBW ~ 1.4 +/- 0.3 deg
#   cut 183_kumar_best_h_120: HPBW ~ 1.0 +/- 0.3 deg (main lobe 3 deg between nulls per text, p. 87)
#   others: main lobe distorted or grid too coarse — not read.
